==================================================
PROJECT VISION
==================================================

Shanelle Store is a premium women's fashion ecommerce platform inspired by the shopping experience of SHEIN.

The objective is NOT to clone SHEIN.

The objective is to reproduce the same level of usability, shopping flow, product discovery, and mobile-first experience while maintaining a unique Shanelle brand identity.

The visual identity must use soft pastel colors, especially pastel pinks, warm neutrals, and elegant feminine tones.

Never copy SHEIN branding, logos, graphics, copyrighted assets, or proprietary layouts.

Instead, reproduce the following UX principles:

• Image-first shopping experience
• Fast browsing
• Large product grids
• Minimal cognitive load
• Clean product pages
• Mobile-first interactions
• Quick product discovery
• Simple checkout flow
• Smooth navigation
• Premium fashion presentation

==================================================
BUSINESS OBJECTIVES
==================================================

The primary objective is to create a scalable women's fashion store for the Nicaragua market.

The customer must be able to:

• Manage products directly in WooCommerce.
• Organize products by seasons.
• Organize products by clothing type.
• Organize products by collections.
• Manage inventory.
• Manage prices.
• Manage promotions.
• Manage coupons.
• Receive online payments.

The website must support future expansion into Latin America.

The architecture should remain scalable.

==================================================
CATALOG EXPERIENCE
==================================================

The catalog experience should feel effortless.

Example categories

• Summer
• Winter
• Casual
• Sleepwear
• Dresses
• Sportswear
• Accessories

Category pages should immediately display products.

Never require unnecessary navigation.

Users should reach a product in as few clicks as possible.

Filtering must be simple.

Product cards should prioritize photography.

Product pages should emphasize

Images

Price

Size

Color

Quantity

Add to Cart

Everything else is secondary.

==================================================
UX PRINCIPLES
==================================================

Reduce cognitive load.

Avoid unnecessary menus.

Avoid complex side navigation.

Avoid information overload.

Present product options directly inside the product page.

Keep interfaces clean.

Prioritize shopping over navigation.

Every page should answer one question:

"What does the customer want to do next?"

The answer should always be obvious.

==================================================
PAYMENT
==================================================

WooCommerce remains the commerce engine.

The design must support future integration with

Stripe

PayPal

PixelPay

BAC Credomatic

Other Latin American payment gateways.

Do not hardcode payment providers.

Use WooCommerce gateways.

==================================================
HOSTING
==================================================

Development

FlyEnv

Production

Hostinger

Do not implement features that depend on a specific hosting provider.

Keep deployment portable.

Avoid vendor lock-in.

==================================================
PWA
==================================================

The website is the primary product.

The PWA will be built only after the website is production complete.

All components should remain PWA-ready.

JavaScript modules should expose reusable APIs whenever appropriate.

Do not build PWA-specific code until the web storefront is finalized.

==================================================
PLUGIN POLICY
==================================================

Before implementing any feature

Check

1. WooCommerce

2. Mature WordPress plugins

3. Custom development

Custom development should only be used when it improves the Shanelle brand experience or when no reliable plugin exists.

Prefer configuration over code whenever possible.

See also: PLUGIN FIRST ARCHITECTURE below and docs/PLUGIN_FIRST_ARCHITECTURE.md.

==================================================
PLUGIN FIRST PRINCIPLE
==================================================

Shanelle Store follows a Plugin First Architecture.

Before writing any code, Cursor must always determine whether the requested functionality already exists as a reliable WordPress or WooCommerce plugin.

Never reinvent mature plugin functionality.

Official guideline:

docs/PLUGIN_FIRST_ARCHITECTURE.md

==================================================
THEME RESPONSIBILITY
==================================================

The theme is responsible only for

• UI

• UX

• WooCommerce presentation

• Components

• Design System

• Layout

• Styling

• Theme Customizer

The theme must never become a business logic application.

==================================================
PLUGIN RESPONSIBILITY
==================================================

Plugins are responsible for

SEO

Analytics

Payments

Shipping

Social Commerce

Authentication

Caching

Security

Forms

Email

Product Feeds

Catalog Sync

Pixels

Tracking

Any third-party service

==================================================
PLUGIN EVALUATION
==================================================

Before implementing a feature, Cursor must evaluate:

1. Does an official plugin exist?

2. Is it actively maintained?

3. Is it WooCommerce compatible?

4. Can it be extended using hooks?

5. Does it solve at least 90 percent of the requirement?

If YES

Recommend using the plugin.

If NO

Document why.

Only then write custom code.

==================================================
CUSTOM DEVELOPMENT
==================================================

Custom code is allowed only when

No plugin exists.

The plugin is abandoned.

The plugin cannot satisfy business requirements.

Performance requires replacement.

The client explicitly requests custom implementation.

==================================================
INTEGRATION RULES
==================================================

Never place integration logic inside UI components.

Integrations belong inside

inc/integrations/

Each integration must remain isolated.

Examples

inc/integrations/stripe

inc/integrations/paypal

inc/integrations/cargo-mobil

inc/integrations/meta

inc/integrations/tiktok

inc/integrations/google

==================================================
PLUGIN COMPATIBILITY
==================================================

The theme must always remain compatible with

WooCommerce

Rank Math

Meta for WooCommerce

TikTok for WooCommerce

Google Site Kit

Stripe

PayPal

PixelPay

BAC Credomatic

LiteSpeed Cache

Hostinger Cache

Wordfence

Fluent Forms

WPML

Polylang

TranslatePress

Advanced Custom Fields

==================================================
NEVER
==================================================

Never modify plugin files.

Never overwrite plugin business logic.

Never duplicate plugin functionality.

Never bypass WooCommerce APIs.

Never tightly couple the theme to a plugin.

==================================================
WHEN A PLUGIN IS INSTALLED
==================================================

The theme should

Detect it.

Enhance it.

Style it.

Extend it using hooks.

Remain operational if the plugin is disabled whenever possible.

==================================================
LONG TERM ARCHITECTURE
==================================================

The project should always remain ready for

PWA

Mobile Apps

REST API

Headless Commerce

Additional Payment Gateways

Additional Shipping Providers

Additional Social Commerce Platforms

without requiring a theme rewrite.

==================================================
CODE REVIEW RULE
==================================================

Before proposing any custom implementation, Cursor must explicitly explain

Why an existing plugin is insufficient.

What business requirement cannot be achieved.

Why custom code is justified.

If this justification cannot be provided, Cursor should recommend the plugin instead.